
Jazz Semiconductor userware  - Information on cbr netlister
_______________________________________________________________

_______________________________________
Top level CBR netlister for import/synth blocks
_______________________________________

The CBR netlister allows reuse of previous design from other design systems.
The global cbr file is generated using information available from Composer's 
schematic sheets and from existing cbr/ckm/cdl files of blocks synthesized
using digital behavioral language (like Verilog) and/or cbr files generated 
by previously supported schematic capture tools (e.g. Logic Assist by Compass). 
To allow the assembly of these different blocks, a top-level schematic 
containing both regular schematic blocks and symbols pointing to cbr/ckm/cdl 
netlists has to be created in Composer. Such symbols must have the following
properties:

  synth_to_cbr=ckm	if the referenced cbr/cdl/ckm file has been synthesized from
			a Verilog description and generated by ver2lvs;
  import_to_cbr=ckm/cdlnoedit	
			if the referenced cbr/ckm/cdl file comes from a LogicAssist 
			schematic capture. This property and the previous one
			are mutually exclusive;
  order=P1 P2 ... Pn	List of pins ordered according to the ".subckt" 
			statement of the top-level cell in the cbr/ckm netlist.
			This property is optional;


When specifying synth_to_cbr=ckm/import_to_cbr=ckm, the cbr netlister reads in the netlist
and substitutes the global nodes with local nodes (i.e. vdd>p, vss>n, vsub>sub),
which are then added to the ".subckt" I/O statement. Every Composer's symbol
is expected to have its supply, substrate and ground nodes defined as pins.

When specifying import_to_cbr=cbrnoedit/ckmnoedit/cdlnoedit, the cbr netlister reads in 
the netlist generated from Logic Assist. The netlist has already its power supply, 
substrate and ground nodes defined locally, hence the cbr netlist is not edited 
but just included in the top level cbr netlist.

The netlist file locations are defined using the following environment variables:

setenv  RDS_COMPOSER_SYNTH	your_ckm_dir1:your_ckm_dir2:...
setenv  RDS_COMPOSER_IMPORT	your_cbr_dir1:your_cbr_dir2:...

_______________________________________
.GLOBAL statement
_______________________________________
If you want to have the .GLOBAL line for global signals, set the environment variable 
RDS_CDS_NL_GLOBAL to "on" before invoking Cadence tool (default is off in Newport Beach):

setenv RDS_CDS_NL_GLOBAL on

_______________________________________
cbr.ini file for configuration
_______________________________________

If ./cbr.ini file exists, use ./cbr.ini file. 
If no ./cbr.ini, but the file specified by environment variable RSS_CDS_CBR_INI exists, use the file.
Otherwise, no file is used for cbr netlist configuration.

In the cbr.ini file, you may specify: 
1. [globalsuffix] : If you want to append "_cds_global" to the global signals, put "y" under [globalsuffix]. By default, no suffix is appended to global signals.
2. [ignore] : A list of cells to be ignored.
3. [busformat] : If you want to use [] for busses, put "[" under [busformat]. By default, <> is used for busses.
4. [header] : header statements to be added to the beginning of the cell.cbr file to be generated.
5. [instnameforbus] : If you want to use _ for instance name for busses, put "_" under [instnameforbus]. By default, <> is used for busses.

Note: "#" at the beginning of lines is used as comment sign.

Example cbr.ini file:
=======================
[header]
.GLOBAL vss vdd
[busformat]
[
[instnameforbus]
_
[globalsuffix]
y
[ignore]
asheet
bsheet
=======================

_______________________________________
The batch mode netlisters:
_______________________________________
usage: nlcbr cellname libname

Note: The nelisters need to be invoked from the directory in which you invoke Cadence system.
      libname can be ignored if your libname is ${PROJ_ID}_${LOGNAME}
      eg: ch25akit_test5 when login as test5 for ch25akit project.
      No Composer license is needed for using batch mode netlisters.

_______________________________________
output directory
_______________________________________
If environment variable CBR_DIR is set, the netlist is generated in the directory specified by CBR_DIR. Otherwise, the netlist is generated in the current directory.
